<div class="row">
<div align="center" class="col-xs-12"><h2><b>5. Nakshatras</b></h2></div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row" style="line-height:24px;">
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
<div>
In Vedic astrology, the zodiac is divided into 27 nakshatras. Each nakshatra has a
length of 360<sup>0</sup>/27 = 13<sup>0</sup> 20'. Each nakshatra is again divided into 4 quarters. 
They are called padas (legs/feet). The length of a nakshatra pada is 3<sup>0</sup> 20'.
The last quarter of Uttarashadha is known as "Abhijit".
</div>
<div class="list-group">
<div class="list-group-item">
For the purpose of some special charts like Kota Chakra and Sarvatobhadra Chakra,
we consider 28 nakshatras.
</div><!--/list-group-item -->
</div><!--/list-group -->
